                            BFormat, Version 4.0

                               by Nick J. Cook
    ____
   (_  _)
    / / n a letter, Horace Walpole wrote "it was said of old Sarah,
   / / Duchess of Marlborough, that she never puts dots over her i's, to
 _/ / save ink". I may not be that bad, but I do tend to be "thrifty,"
(____) like using a printer ribbon until the print is only legible on the
       Bold setting. The BFormat PD utility is for all fellow cheap-
skates. AmigaDOS formats only perfect diskettes; even if only one block
is "bad," AmigaDOS deems the entire disk  unusable. BFormat is a CLI-only
utility that allows you to format those less than pristine disks by
mapping out the errors. The program supports the Fast File System, any
type of floppy disk, hard drive partitions, and RAD: devices. The only
limitation is that Track 0 and Track 80 must be good.

BFormat camouflages the bad blocks from AmigaDOS. When a block cannot be
formatted, the program marks it as "in use". These marked blocks are not
attached to any specific AmigaDOS file, so AmigaDOS doesn't attempt to
use them.

The BFormat command contains switches to flag for the file system type,
as well as the options FAST, QUICK, and SLOW. The latter verifies each
track with four different patterns, and lives up to its name.

I have used BFormat only on floppies. One disk contained 22 bad sectors.
After BFormat completed its task, the disk indicated that it was 1%
full -- those were the bad sectors. Two cautions, though:

 1) BFormat does _not_ restore data; all data on the disk will be lost,
    just as with a regular "format" command;

 2) If your disk has one hard track error, that may be a sign that the
    disk is on its way out, so don't put your life's work on one.

BFormat is a cinch to use, even to those of us who use the CLI as a last
resort. The docs are concise and easy to understand.

BFormat Authors: T.A. Nery, R.W. Bowers, Bob Bush
*StarShip* File #10428  BFORMAT4.LZH
Also available on: Fish Disk 758.







ViewPort March, 1993  ------------------------------------------  Page 11

                              Laboratory of Life

                               by Joseph A. Grau
    ____
   (_  _)
    / / 've always been a big believer in old sayings like "There's no
   / / such thing as a free lunch" and "You get what you pay for."  If
 _/ / someone gives me something for nothing, I figure it's gonna turn
(____) out to be worth every cent I paid for it.  So what happens?
      Along comes Accursed Toys and demolishes my belief in old sayings.

"Laboratory of Life" is a game, recently released by the two halves of
Accursed Toys -- Jennifer Diane Reitz and Stephen P. Lepisto -- as freely
distributable software.  When I saw it in the GEnie download libraries, I
figured it mustn't be much, or they wouldn't be just giving it away.
Shows how much I know.  I wish some of the commercial game software I've
bought had the class of this package.

If you've been around computing any time at all, you've undoubtedly run
across several versions of the "Game of Life" -- a simulation/game in
which "cells" endure, multiply, and die based on their position relative
to neighboring cells.  You can watch population explosions, stagnation of
civilizations, urban crowding, and even the extinction of species right
on your monitor.

Accursed Toys has taken this basic concept and turned it into a very
entertaining game.  And, if you would prefer a bit more serious
exploration of the subject, they've provided all the tools you need to
study this fascinating aspect of artificial life in detail.

A basic game starts you off with a small colony of four cells in the
middle of the screen.  You are able to influence these cells by
point-and-click "lightning strikes" which create new cells.  Your object
is to keep the colony alive and growing, which you do with judicious use
of your lightning strikes.  Depending on which of the four levels of
difficulty you select, you must keep the colony flourishing for from 250
to 1000 generations.  Points are scored for each life created, with
bonuses for the size of the final generation and unused lightning strikes.

That's the game, now what makes it special?  Three things.  The first is
the configurability of the game, which should stave off boredom even for
accomplished gamers.  You not only have four levels of difficulty, but
you can also establish "blind spots" where neighbors will not be counted
in the life/reproduction/death calculations, call for random lightning
strikes to complicate matters, vary the wraparound effect at the screen
borders, and adjust the speed of the game.

Next come the cells themselves.  There are eighteen sets of cell graphics
provided on the menu, all done by the wickedly creative Jennifer Diane
Reitz.  Want to watch a circuit board populate and depopulate itself with
components?  Choose "Electronica."  Pick "Go" if you are in the mood for
the dignified serenity of the ancient Oriental game.  Or try
"Snotglobble" for a slightly queasy chuckle.  Each graphic set is
cleverly crafted to provide animation as the cells are born and die.

                                             (Continued on next page)








ViewPort March, 1993  ------------------------------------------  Page 12


The last thing that makes this game special is simply the high quality of
the "look and feel" of the package.  The menus are well thought-out, game
control is simple and natural enough that even *I* can handle it, and the
readily accessible help and information are very well done.  All the
little details seem to have been carefully considered, and concern with
quality is evident throughout.

Of course, if you tire of the game, you can always start seriously
exploring the system by drawing your own cell patterns and trying them
out with a variety of rules and conditions.  Everything you need is
available right on the same menus you used for playing the game.

All in all, this is a first rate, highly professional product.  If I had
to find a quibble, it would be with the background music.  Not bad music
at all, but it wore out its welcome with me rather quickly.  (Some nice
soft Baroque next time, maybe?)  There is a ready menu option to turn off
the music, though, which I have become quite adept at using.

Laboratory of Life seems to multitask quite nicely on my 600HD under 2.1.
At least it gets along well with Baud Bandit and Turbo Text.  It also
works under 1.3, and is non-laced so you won't be flickered to death.

Laboratory of Life can be found in Starship Library 9 as file 18313,
LABOFLIFE.LHA.  And if you try the game and like it, please take a minute
to stop by Category 30 in the Starship Bulletin Board and say "thanks."
And while you're there, look around for information and news about
Accursed Toys' other products and projects.


Editor's Addendum:

After a bit of flak related to the "deadie bear" mascot of Accursed Toys,
Jennifer and Stephen went back to work and created "Accursed Toys Junior
Software," which is responsible for software for the "very young.  Their
first release under this line is PeekABoo, described as "the world's
first and possibly only peek-a-boo simulator."  We are assured that no
bears "were harmed nor even inconvenienced to bring you this software."

So what is it?  The title says it all.  It's a peek-a-boo simulator,
featuring Twirliquin, the Friendly Bear.  When you run this gem,
Twirliquin appears, sitting on the floor amidst a few toys.  Twirliquin
fidgets, making noise from time to time, and - every once in a while -
uncovers his eyes and says "Peek-a-Boo!"  All of this is accompanied by a
Carcassi score.

PeekABoo is unbearably cute - pun intended - and there are surprises in
store if you hit any keys.  The F1 and F2 keys, in particular, are
dedicated to particular effects.  What are they?  You'll have to download
PeekABoo and see for yourself.  As one noted Amiga editor/journalist
(with a newly-released book featuring Amiga secrets and tips) remarked,
"It's GREAT, too.  Makes me want to go out and have a kid so he/she can
enjoy it."

PEEKABOO.LHA can be found in the *StarShip* library as file #18619.

ACCURSED TOYS
470 Mt. Defiance Cir. SW
Issaquah, WA 980027-3629





ViewPort March, 1993  ------------------------------------------  Page 13

                         Running with ARexx (Part 3)
                               by Robin Evans

We tried to work up a sweat last time out by taking a tough jog with a
real-world ARexx program. If you're just starting out on your ARexx
regimen, some parts of the that program may have been confusing. Don't
worry. There will be time for chalk talk later -- time to address some of
the questions and issues of style which have arisen.

First though, we should finish the initial jog. As it was presented last
time, the UnCrunch program could handle only .LHA and .LHZ files. The
function presented at the end of this month's tutorial will make the
program more versatile.

What we want to create is a single simple command structure for any
uncrunching program. That was easy to do with the 'LHA' or 'LZ' programs
since they will accept both the name of the archive file and the name of a
directory where its files will be dissolved. Most other archivers, however,
dissolve files only into the current directory.

It's simple enough to change the current directory, since ARexx can send a
'CD' command to AmigaDOS. The problem is that we can't be sure the user has
supplied a filename which can be understood from the new directory. The
'SetDest' function checks the file name and gives it a full
'device:path/file' name, no matter how it was originally specified.

This is an ideal task for a function since the same code can be used in
several slightly different ways. It saves space and makes the program more
readable.

                          (ALMOST) FULLY FUNCTIONAL

Functions can be used in either of two forms which make them easy to spot.
The symbol or word used to identify the function is either followed by a set
of parentheses or it is preceded by the keyword CALL. (Parentheses may be
used even with the CALL keyword, as they were in lines 24, 26, and 28 of the
UnCrunch program, but are not necessary.) In either of these forms, a series
of other values, called arguments, can be added after the function name and
between the parentheses, if used. These arguments are passed to the function.

In the main section of UnCrunch.rexx presented last month, the function
'SetDest' is called with this statement:

      call SetDest('ZOO x//')

The quoted string within the parenthesis is sent to the subroutine SetDest.
(In last month's listing there was a space between 'x' and '//' which should
be deleted.) In this month's code section, that value is picked up in line
40 by the statement 'parse arg AProg' which sets the value of the variable
AProg to 'ZOO x//'. (Remember that PARSE ARG, unlike ARG by itself, does not
convert the argument to uppercase. Zoo won't work with an 'X' as a command
argument.) That value is then used in line 69 to execute the uncrunching.

Although the RETURN keyword is used here in solo, it could also be used to
return an argument (like 'RETURN 0'). If that were done, then the returned
value could be assigned to a variable as it is in line 47, which uses a
'built-in function'.

                                                   (Continued on next page)





ViewPort March, 1993  ------------------------------------------  Page 14

                             TYPES OF FUNCTIONS

SetDest is called an internal function because it is defined within the
program from which it is called. The colon after 'SetDest:' in the first
line of this month's code tells ARexx that the program lines which follow
are part of a function. The keyword RETURN at the end of the listing
indicates the end of the function and returns control to the point in the
program where there function was called.

Another function, SUBSTR(), is used in line 49. Like RIGHT() which was used
in the main program, this is a built-in function. It's part of ARexx itself
and will always be available to any ARexx program. Your ARexx manual lists
all of the built-in functions as well as the 'syntax' used to call them --
the arguments which must be supplied for the function to do its work.

A third, and very useful type of function, is supplied by external 'function
libraries' or 'function hosts'. These libraries make ARexx extendable. For
instance, even though REXX and all of the built-in functions used by ARexx
were developed over a decade ago on IBM mainframe computers where windows,
requesters, and mice were but a Xerox dream, ARexx still has full access to
those Intuition features on the Amiga through external functions.

 /************************************************************************
    Add this section to the UnCrunch.rexx program. Replace 'SetDest:' and
    everything which follows it in the original version with this section.
 ========================================================================*/

       SetDest:
 /*40*/   parse arg AProg
          cdir = pragma('D')              /* Store the current directory */

          /* Change archive filename to a path/file that can be          */
          /* understood from a different directory                       */
 /*45*/ FDir = CDir   /* FDir will be altered. CDir needs to be unchanged*/
        select        /* The variable FileName is 'borrowed' from above  */
          when pos(':', FileName) > 1 then
             FDir = ''   /* device is already specified. Don't change it */
          when substr(FileName, 1,1) = '/' then do
                /* Strip off leading '/' in filename */
             do while substr(FileName, 1,1) = '/'    /* is 1st char '/'? */
                FileName = substr(FileName, 2)       /* strip it off     */
                   /* The next 2 lines are 1 program line. The extra     */
                   /* comma at the end of the 1st line marks continuation*/
                DivPos = max(lastpos('/', FDir, length(FDir)-1),,
                    lastpos(':', FDir))
                FDir = left(FDir, DivPos)
             end
          end
          when substr(FileName,1,1) = ':' then
             parse var cdir FDir ':' .
          otherwise
             FDir = CDir
 /*64*/ end
        FileName = FDir||FileName

        'cd "'UCdir'"'   /* These three commands won't be understood by  */
                         /* ARexx, so they will be sent on to the 'host  */
 /*69*/ AProg FileName   /* address'. Since UnCrunch was executed from   */
                         /* the shell, that's where the commands will go */
        'cd "'CDir'"'    /* AmigaDOS will know exactly what to do...     */
        return
   /*  [End of Program] Stop highlighting text on the line above this one.
 *************************************************************************/

